      "output": "**Water** is a simple chemical compound that is essential for life on Earth. Here’s a concise overview of what water is, how it’s structured, and why it matters:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Chemical Identity\n- **Formula:** **H₂O** – each molecule consists of two hydrogen atoms covalently bonded to one oxygen atom.\n- **Molecular weight:** ≈ 18.015 g/mol.\n- **Bond angle:** ≈ 104.5°, giving the molecule a bent (V‑shaped) geometry.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Physical States\n| State | Typical Conditions | Key Characteristics |\n|-------|--------------------|----------------------|\n| **Solid (Ice)** | ≤ 0 °C (32 °F) | Crystalline lattice, less dense than liquid water (hence ice floats). |\n| **Liquid** | 0 °C – 100 °C (32 °F – 212 °F) at 1 atm | Highly cohesive, excellent solvent, high surface tension, high specific heat capacity. |\n| **Gas (Water Vapor/Steam)** | ≥ 100 °C (212 °F) at 1 atm | Invisible gas; when condensed, forms clouds, fog, or steam. |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Unique Physical & Chemical Properties\n| Property | Why It’s Important |\n|----------|-------------------|\n| **Polarity** | The uneven charge distribution makes water a superb solvent for ionic and polar substances. |\n| **Hydrogen bonding** | Weak bonds between water molecules give rise to high boiling point, surface tension, and the anomalous density maximum at 4 °C. |\n| **High specific heat (4.18 J·g⁻¹·K⁻¹)** | Buffers temperature changes, stabilizing climates and biological systems. |\n| **High heat of vaporization (≈ 2260 kJ·kg⁻¹)** | Drives evaporative cooling (e.g., sweating). |\n| **Cohesion & adhesion** | Enables capillary action, crucial for plant water transport. |\n| **Density anomaly** | Ice is ~9 % less dense than liquid water, allowing it to float and insulate aquatic life in winter. |\n\n---\n\n"
